ts Fish.\n\nMethod 1: Counting Favorable vs Total Outcomes\nTotal number of ways to distribute the meals.\nWe have 6 crew members. We need to assign 3 Fish and 3 Steaks to them.\nThis is equivalent to choosing which 3 crew members get Fish. The remaining 3 will get Steaks.\nThe number of ways to choose 3 crew members out of 6 to receive Fish is $\\binom{6}{3}$.\n$\\binom{6}{3} = \\frac{6 \\times 5 \\times 4}{3 \\times 2 \\times 1} = 20$.\nThese are all the distinct scenarios of meal distribution based on who gets Fish. Since the problem states "distributed randomly", each of these scenarios is equally likely.\n\nFavorable outcomes:\nWe want both pilots to get Fish.\nLet the two pilots be a subset of the 6 crew members.\nFor them to get Fish, they must be included in the set of 3 crew members chosen to receive Fish.\nSo, we need to choose the remaining $3 - 2 = 1$ crew member to receive Fish from the remaining $6 - 2 = 4$ crew members.\nThe number of ways to choose this 1 crew member is $\\binom{4}{1}$.\n$\\binom{4}{1} = 4$.\n\nProbability $P = \\frac{\\text{Number of favorable outcomes}}{\\text{Total number of outcomes}} = \\frac{\\binom{4}{1}}{\\binom{6}{3}}$.\n$P = \\frac{4}{20}$.\nSimplify the fraction: $P = \\frac{1}{5}$.\n\nMethod 2: Sequential probability\nImagine the meals are distributed one by one or just look at the specific pilots.\nLet\'s look at the meal pile. It contains 3 Fish and 3 Steaks. Total 6.\nPilot 1 picks a meal. The probability that Pilot 1 gets Fish is:\n$P(P_1 = F) = \\frac{3}{6} = \\frac{1}{2}$.\nNow, assuming Pilot 1 got Fish, there are 5 meals left: 2 Fish and 3 Steaks.\nPilot 2 picks a meal. The probability that Pilot 2 gets Fish, given Pilot 1 got Fish, is:\n$P(P_2 = F | P_1 = F) = \\frac{2}{5}$.\nThe probability that both get Fish is the product of these probabilities.\n$P(Both F) = \\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{2}{5} = \\frac{2}{10} = \\frac{1}{5}$.\n\nLet\'s double check the wording.\n"Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\n"If the meals are distributed to the crew members randomly..."\n"what is the probability that both pilots get the fish?"\n\nAssumptions made:\n1. There are exactly 2 pilots in the 6-member crew. The term "both pilots" implies there are two pilots. If there were more, it would say "all pilots" or specific names. "Both" usually implies a count of 2. If a flight crew of 6 contains 2 pilots and 4 flight attendants (or similar), the logic holds.\n   Is it possible there are 3 pilots? Usually, standard commercial planes have 2 pilots. A flight attendant of 6-member crew context suggests a small plane or specific logistics. If there were 3 pilots, "both" would be confusing. So 2 pilots is the standard interpretation.\n2. The distribution is random.\n3. The meal types are the distinguishing factor.\n\nLet\'s re-read carefully to ensure no misinterpretation.\n"Six-member crew".\n"Three steak meals and three fish meals".\n"Both pilots".\n\nIs there any ambiguity about the pilots being among the crew?\nUsually, pilots are part of the crew. If pilots were sitting at the front and crew were at the back, it might be separate. But here it says "for the six-member crew". It implies pilots are part of that set.\nLet\'s verify the "Guide" prompt: "An airline serves a dinner to all the passengers on an airplane. They get their choice of steak or fish. Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nWait, the text says "serves a dinner to all the passengers" but then "set aside for the six-member crew".\nDoes this mean the dinner is only for the crew?\n"Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nThis phrasing suggests that the specific meal allocation problem concerns the crew\'s dinner.\nUsually, passengers eat dinner too.\nHowever, the question asks specifically about the crew\'s meal distribution. "If the meals are distributed to the crew members randomly".\nThe context "serves a dinner to all the passengers" seems like flavor text setting the scene (e.g., maybe the crew meals are the leftovers or just a specific mix), but the constraint applies to the crew. Or perhaps the "passengers" part is irrelevant context, or maybe a typo in the problem statement provided.\nLet\'s assume the pool of meals available for the crew is strictly defined: 3 Steaks, 3 Fish.\nAnd the recipients are the 6 crew members.\nAnd we need to find the probability that the 2 pilots (who are a subset of the 6 crew) receive Fish.\n\nLet\'s assume the interpretation that $N=6$ crew members and there are 2 pilots.\nIf the problem meant that the crew is distinct from the pilots, the answer would be 0 or undefined if pilots aren\'t receiving meals. But it says "distributed to the crew members". So pilots must be crew members.\nIf the problem meant that there are $k$ pilots in the crew, "both" implies $k=2$.\n\nLet\'s re-evaluate the calculation.\nMethod 1 result: $1/5$.\nMethod 2 result: $1/5$.\n$m = 1$, $n = 5$.\n$gcd(1, 5) = 1$.\n$m + n = 6$.\n\nLet\'s check if there are other interpretations.\nWhat if the pilots are not included in the 6-member crew?\n"Crew" usually includes the flight deck.\nIf "passengers" are mentioned first, maybe dinner is for everyone.\n"Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nThis sounds like specific meals for the crew are pre-selected.\nTotal meals for crew = 6.\nCrew size = 6.\nThis is a 1-to-1 mapping.\nSo the previous logic holds perfectly.\n\nLet\'s double check if "Six-member crew" implies specific roles.\nUsually, a cockpit crew consists of 2 pilots. A flight deck surge? No, standard is 2.\nIf the problem came from a contest (like AMC or similar), "both pilots" implies there are exactly two pilots.\nIf there were 4 pilots, "both" would be incorrect usage for "all of them".\nSo 2 pilots is a safe assumption.\n\nLet\'s consider the phrase "They get their choice of steak or fish."\nThis could mean passengers