r choice of steak or fish. Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nThe passengers get their choice?\nMaybe the total supply in the galley is something else, but the crew is restricted to the 3S and 3F meals?\nOr does "Three steak meals and three fish meals" refer to the meals set aside *from* the passenger order?\nRegardless, the condition "set aside for the six-member crew" and "distributed to the crew members" seems to define the sample space for the crew only. The reference to passengers and "choice" might be irrelevant filler or context for why these specific meals exist (maybe the passengers got everything else, or the crew needed to eat, and there were only 6 meals left?).\nActually, if passengers get choice, the number of meals allocated to the pilot depends on the passengers\' choices?\nWait. "They get their choice of steak or fish." "They" refers to "all the passengers".\nThen "Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nThis sentence structure in math problems usually defines the premises for the specific question.\nPremise 1: There are a set of 6 meals (3S, 3F) reserved for the crew.\nPremise 2: These 6 meals are distributed to the 6 crew members randomly.\nPremise 3: We are interested in the event where the two pilots get Fish.\n\nIs there any chance the "crew" does not include the pilots?\nA "crew" of an airplane includes pilots, flight attendants, etc.\nIf the problem meant crew members work, it would imply crew. Pilots fly.\nIn aviation terminology, "crew" refers to everyone on board operating the plane (flight staff).\nSometimes "ground crew" vs "flight crew".\nHowever, in these math puzzles, unless specified "flight attendants" vs "pilots", usually "crew" encompasses everyone.\nAlso, the text says "set aside for the six-member crew". Then "distributed to the crew members". Then asks about "both pilots".\nIf pilots were not crew members, they wouldn\'t be "crew members" getting distributed meals.\nOr, if pilots were separate, we would need to know how many meals are for them. But the text says meals *are set aside for the six-member crew*. So the pilots are likely part of the six.\nAlso "six-member crew" is a small number for a plane with passengers (usually 2 pilots + 3-5 attendants = 6-8 staff). For a small aircraft, there are 2 pilots + 4 attendants or even just a co-pilot + pilot + tech, etc.\nGiven the "six-member" vs "both pilots", it strongly supports the set of 6 containing the 2 pilots.\n\nLet\'s double check the "randomly" part.\nIf it\'s random, every assignment is equiprobable.\nCalculation holds.\n\nIs there any ambiguity in "both pilots"?\nDoes it mean "at least two pilots"? No, "both" is specific.\nDoes it mean "the two pilots" (assuming standard 2)? Yes.\n\nWhat if the "choice" of passengers affects the number of meals?\n"An airline serves a dinner to all the passengers... They get their choice... Three steak meals and three fish meals are set aside for the six-member crew."\nThis could be interpreted as: The total manifest was for X passengers. Plus 6 crew.\nHowever, we are only given information about the meals for the crew.\nIf the meal distribution for the crew depends on what the passengers chose (e.g. "The airline sets aside 3S and 3F *for the crew*"), it implies these are the meals *available* for the crew.\nDoes the fact that passengers get a choice imply anything about the meal availability?\nMaybe the crew *chose*? No, "set aside" implies pre-determination.\nAlso "distributed... randomly" implies no choice by crew members.\nSo the only numbers that matter are:\nAvailable meals for crew: 3S, 3F.\nCrew size: 6.\nTarget: Pilots (subset of crew).\nCount: Total pilots = 2 (implied by "both").\nTarget state: Pilots get Fish.\n\nLet\'s assume the ambiguity about the number of pilots.\n"Both pilots" is a standard phrase in English problems where the number of pilots is implicitly 2. If there were 3 pilots, "both" would