e term to subtract is $|S_{15} \\cup S_{20}|$.\nUsing the inclusion-exclusion principle again:\n$|S_{15} \\cup S_{20}| = |S_{15}| + |S_{20}| - |S_{15} \\cap S_{20}|$.\n$S_{15} \\cap S_{20} = S_{\\text{lcm}(15,20)}$.\n$\\text{lcm}(15, 20) = \\text{lcm}(3 \\cdot 5, 4 \\cdot 5) = 3 \\cdot 4 \\cdot 5 = 60$.\nSo the term is $|S_{60}|$.\n\nLet\'s summarize the formula:\nTarget Count = $N = (|S_3| + |S_4| - |S_{12}|) - (|S_{15}| + |S_{20}| - |S_{60}|)$.\n\nThe number of multiples of $k$ in the range $1 \\le n \\le N_{range}$ is given by $\\lfloor \\frac{N_{range}}{k} \\rfloor$.\nHere $N_{range} = 2001$.\n\nLet\'s calculate each term.\n1. $|S_3| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{3} \\rfloor$.\n2001 is divisible by 3 since sum of digits is $2+0+0+1 = 3$.\nSo $|S_3| = 667$.\n\n2. $|S_4| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{4} \\rfloor$.\n$2000$ is divisible by 4. $2001 = 4 \\times 500 + 1$.\nSo $|S_4| = 500$.\n\n3. $|S_{12}| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{12} \\rfloor$.\n$2001 = 12 \\times 166 + 9$.\n$12 \\times 100 = 1200$.\n$12 \\times 60 = 720$.\n$12 \\times 6 = 72$.\n$1200 + 720 + 72 = 1992$.\n$2001 - 1992 = 9$.\nSo $|S_{12}| = 166$.\nAlternatively, $2001/12 = 100.05/6 \\approx 166.75$.\nLet\'s check: $12 \\times 166 = 12(100 + 60 + 6) = 1200 + 720 + 72 = 1992$. Correct.\n\n4. $|S_{15}| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{15} \\rfloor$.\n$2001 = 15 \\times 133 + 6$.\n$15 \\times 100 = 1500$.\n$2001 - 1500 = 501$.\n$501 / 15$: $15 \\times 30 = 450$.\n$501 - 450 = 51$.\n$15 \\times 3 = 45$.\n$51 - 45 = 6$.\nSo $100 + 30 + 3 = 133$.\nWait, $15 \\times 133 = 15(130 + 3) = 1950 + 45 = 1995$.\nSo $|S_{15}| = 133$.\nAlternatively, $2001 / 15 = 133.4$.\n\n5. $|S_{20}| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{20} \\rfloor$.\n$2000$ is divisible by 20.\nSo $|S_{20}| = 100$.\n\n6. $|S_{60}| = \\lfloor \\frac{2001}{60} \\rfloor$.\n$2001 = 60 \\times 33 + 21$.\n$60 \\times 30 = 1800$.\n$2001 - 1800 = 201$.\n$60 \\times 3 = 180$.\n$201 - 180 = 21$.\nSo $|S_{60}| = 33$.\nAlternatively, $60 \\times 33 = 1980$. $2001 - 1980 = 21$. Correct.\n\nNow substitute these values into the formula for $N$.\n$N = (|S_3| + |S_4| - |S_{12}|) - (|S_{15}| + |S_{20}| - |S_{60}|)$.\n$N = (667 + 500 - 166) - (133 + 100 - 33)$.\n\nLet\'s calculate the first part (multiples of 3 or 4):\n$A = 667 + 500 - 166$.\n$667 + 500 = 1167$.\n$1167 - 166 = 1001$.\nSo there are 1001 numbers divisible by 3 or 4 up to 2001.\n\nLet\'s calculate the second part (multiples of 15 or 20, which are multiples of 5 divisible by 3 or 4):\n$B = 133 + 100 - 33$.\n$133 + 100 = 233$.\n$233 - 33 = 200$.\nSo there are 200 numbers divisible by 5 and (3 or 4) up to 2001.\n\nTotal count = $A - B = 1001 - 200 = 801$.\n\nLet me double check the logic.\nThe set of numbers we want is $(M_3 \\cup M_4) \\setminus M_5$.\nThis is equal to $(M_3 \\cup M_4) \\cap M_5^c$.\nUsing sets properties: $X \\setminus Y = |X| - |X \\cap Y|$.\nSo we need $|(M_3 \\cup M_4)| - |(M_3 \\cup M_4) \\cap M_5|$.\n$(M_3 \\cup M_4) \\cap M_5 = (M_3 \\cap M_5) \\cup (M_4 \\cap M_5)$.\nThis is indeed union of $M_{15}$ and $M_{20}$.\nSo the formula is correct.\n\nLet\'s re-verify the floor calculations.\n$N=2001$.\n$|M_3| = \\lfloor 2001/3 \\rfloor = 667$. (Since $2001/3 = 667$) Correct.\n$|M_4| = \\lfloor 2001/4 \\rfloor = 500$. (Since $2000/4 = 500$, $2001 = 4k+1$) Correct.\n$|M_{12}| = \\lfloor 2001/12 \\rfloor$. $2001/12 = 166.75$. Correct.\n$|M_{15}| = \\lfloor 2001/15 \\rfloor$. $2001/15 = 133.4$. Correct.\n$|M_{20}| = \\lfloor 2001/20 \\rfloor = \\lfloor 100.05 \\rfloor = 100$. Correct.\n$|M_{60}| = \\lfloor 2001/60 \\rfloor$. $2001/60 = 33.35$. Correct.\n\nPart 1: $|M_3 \\cup M_4| = 667 + 500 - 166$.\n$667 + 500 = 1167$.\n$1167 - 166 = 1001$.\nLet\'s check small numbers. Multiples of 3 or 4 up to 12.\nM3: 3, 6, 9, 12. (4)\nM4: 4, 8, 12. (3)\nUnion: 3, 4, 6, 8, 9, 12. (6)\nFormula: $\\lfloor 12/3 \\rfloor + \\lfloor 12/4 \\rfloor - \\lfloor 12/12 \\rfloor = 4 + 3 - 1 = 6$. Correct.\nPart 1 seems robust.\n\nPart 2: $|(M_3 \\cap M_5) \\cup (M_4 \\cap M_5)| = |M_{15} \\cup M_{20}|$.\n$|M_{