} x \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix}$.\nSo the matrix for the gradient term is $2 \\times$ Matrix of quadratic form.\nLet $M_S = \\begin{pmatrix} 3 & 1/2 \\\\ 1/2 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}$. Then $\\nabla S = 2 M_S \\mathbf{v}$.\nLet $M_C = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 & -2 \\\\ -2 & 2 \\end{pmatrix}$. Then $\\nabla C = 2 M_C \\mathbf{v}$.\nLagrange condition: $\\nabla S = \\lambda \\nabla C \\implies 2 M_S \\mathbf{v} = \\lambda (2 M_C \\mathbf{v}) \\implies M_S \\mathbf{v} = \\lambda M_C \\mathbf{v}$.\nThe values of $\\lambda$ here will be the Lagrange multipliers?\nActually, multiply by $\\mathbf{v}^T$:\n$\\mathbf{v}^T M_S \\mathbf{v} = \\lambda \\mathbf{v}^T M_C \\mathbf{v}$.\n$S = \\lambda (C)$. Since $C=1$, $S = \\lambda$.\nSo we need to find the eigenvalues $\\lambda$ of $M_S$ relative to $M_C$.\nThe characteristic equation is $\\det(M_S - \\lambda M_C) = 0$.\n$M_S - \\lambda M_C = \\begin{pmatrix} 3 & 1/2 \\\\ 1/2 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} - \\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} 4 & -2 \\\\ -2 & 2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 3 - 4\\lambda & 1/2 + 2\\lambda \\\\ 1/2 + 2\\lambda & 1 - 2\\lambda \\end{pmatrix}$.\nDeterminant:\n$(3 - 4\\lambda)(1 - 2\\lambda) - (1/2 + 2\\lambda)^2 = 0$\n$3 - 6\\lambda - 4\\lambda + 8\\lambda^2 - (1/4 + 2\\lambda + 4\\lambda^2) = 0$\n$3 - 10\\lambda + 8\\lambda^2 - 1/4 - 2\\lambda - 4\\lambda^2 = 0$\n$4\\lambda^2 - 12\\lambda + (12/4 - 1/4) = 0$\n$4\\lambda^2 - 12\\lambda + \\frac{11}{4} = 0$\nMultiply by 4:\n$16\\lambda^2 - 48\\lambda + 11 = 0$.\nThis is exactly the same quadratic equation as for $m$ in method 1 (where $m=S$).\nSo the possible values for $S$ are the roots of this equation.\nThe roots are $\\frac{48 \\pm \\sqrt{2304 - 704}}{32} = \\frac{48 \\pm 40}{32}$.\n$S_{min} = 1/4$, $S_{max} = 11/4$.\n\nMethod 3: Eigenvalues of a matrix directly related to the ratio.\nConsider the ratio $R = \\frac{3x^2 + xy + y^2}{4x^2 - 4xy + 2y^2}$.\nWe want to find max/min of $R$.\nThis is equivalent to finding eigenvalues of $A^{-1}B$ or similar, but since quadratic forms, we